@article{Diaz9999,
abstract = {The purpose of this study is to assess the ability of a set of Large Ensembles (LE) of 4 climate model simulations from the Multi-Model Large Ensemble Archive, Coupled Model 5 Intercomparison Project Phase 6 (CMIP6) and database for Policy Decision making for 6 Future climate change in reproducing the variability and change of the austral summer 7 precipitation observed in South America along the second part of the 20th century and 8 beginning of the 21st. LE show similar biases in the mean austral summer rainfall and 9 interannual variability than those detected in previous model sets, such as the Coupled 10 Model Intercomparison Project Phase 5 (CMIP5). Austral summer interannual variability is 11 reproduced considerably worse than the mean rainfall. The positive trends in southeastern 12 South America (SESA) and negative ones in the southern Andes (SAn), that are the most 13 significant observed regional features, are identified to some extent in LE simulations. The 14 negative trend in SAn is a feature consistently shown among different models. For all 15 models, mean trend is negative in that particular region and larger than the inter-member 16 dispersion for each large ensemble. Trend magnitudes in the SESA region show a larger 17 dispersion between models than the SAn region. While the mean trend among models is 18 consistent with the observations, models underestimate the observed trend. The multi- 19 model ensemble of selected models that best reproduce both mean and interannual 20 variability features of rainfall in South America shows a larger positive mean trend in SESA 21 rainfall than those that have the worst performance. However, internal variability 22 uncertainty is still higher than the mean trend for both sets of multi-model ensembles. 23 Improvements in the representation of the main features of mean rainfall and variability are 24 needed in order to better describe and reduce the uncertainties associated with the main 25 climate ch