@article{Mindlin2020,
abstract = {As evidence of climate change strengthens; knowledge of its regional 11 implications becomes an urgent need for decision making. Current understanding 12 of regional precipitation changes is substantially limited by our understanding of 13 the atmospheric circulation response to climate change, which to a high degree 14 remains uncertain. This uncertainty is re ected in the wide spread in atmospheric 15 circulation changes projected in multimodel ensembles, which cannot be directly 16 interpreted in a probabilistic sense. The uncertainty can instead be represented 17 by studying a discrete set of physically plausible storylines of atmospheric circula18 tion changes. By mining CMIP5 models output, here we take a broader perspec19 tive and develop storylines for Southern Hemisphere (SH) midlatitude circulation 20 changes, conditioned on the degree of global-mean warming, based on the climate 21 responses of two remote drivers: the upper-tropospheric topical ampli cation of 22 surface warming and the strengthening of the stratospheric polar vortex. For the 23 three continental domains in the SH, we analyse the precipitation changes under each storyline. Based on previous studies, we also linked both circulation and pre25 cipitation changes with those of the Southern Annular Mode. Our results show 26 that the response to a high tropical ampli cation leads to a strengthening of the 27 midlatitude westerly winds, whilst the response to a late breakdown (for DJF) or 28 large strengthening (for JJA) of the stratospheric vortex leads to a poleward shift 29 of the westerly winds and the storm tracks. However, the circulation response is 30 not zonally symmetric and the regional precipitation storylines for South America, 31 South Africa, South Australia and New Zealand exhibit quite speci c dependen32 cies on the two remote drivers, which are not well represented by changes in the 33 Southern Annular Mode.},
